d English personal name <i>Wada</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The Surrey placename derives from Old English <i>hwǣte</i> ‘wheat’, later <i>hwǣten</i> ‘growing with wheat’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’."],"variants":[{"name":"Wadlington","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Waddington   or   Watlington  ."]},{"name":"Weddington","meanings":["English: habitational name from Weddington in Warwickshire, recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Watintune</i>, from an unattested Old English personal name <i>Hwæt</i> + <i>-ing-</i> denoting association with + <i>tūn</i> ‘estate’. However, the surname does not appear in English sources and it may simply be an altered form of   Waddington  ."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":30,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdic